"nl":{"0999–1081":"0999–1081","1000–Female":"1000–Overleden","1025–1081":"1025–1081","0965–Male":"0965–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1025":"1025","about 1025":"circa 1025","1000":"1000","before 0999":"vóór 0999","0965":"0965","0999":"0999","1081":"1081","Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Brecon, Powys, Wales":"Brecon, Powys, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Powys, Wales":"Powys, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"0999–1081":"0999–1081","1000–Female":"1000–Deceased","1025–1081":"1025–1081","0965–Male":"0965–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1025":"1025","about 1025":"about 1025","1000":"1000","before 0999":"before 0999","0965":"0965","0999":"0999","1081":"1081","Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Brecon, Powys, Wales":"Brecon, Powys, Wales, United Kingdom","Powys, Wales":"Powys, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Llywellyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Llywelyn</i>, derived from British Celtic <i>Lugubelinos</i>, itself from the divine name <i>Lugus</i> + an uncertain second element often used alone as a name. Through association with <i>llew</i> ‘lion’, it was altered to <i>Llewelyn</i>. This was the name of two princes of north Wales who held the Normans at bay for many years in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."],"variants":[{"name":"Lewelling","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Llewellyn  ."]},{"name":"Lewellen","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Llewellyn  ."]},{"name":"Lewallen","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Llewellyn  ."]},{"name":"Louallen","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh <b>Llewelyn</b> (see   Llewellyn  )."]},{"name":"Luellen","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Llewellyn  ."]},{"name":"Welling","meanings":["English: habitational name from Welwyn (Hertfordshire) or Welling in Bexley (Kent), with a suspicion of an alternative unidentified source. The Hertfordshire placename means ‘at the willow trees’, from Old English <i>wel(i)gum</i>, dative plural form of <i>welig</i> ‘willow’. The Kent placename may derive from Old English <i>wella</i> ‘well, spring, stream’ + the placename forming suffix <i>-ing</i>. In some cases this name may represent a development of   Llewellyn  , particularly near the Welsh border.","German: habitational name from any of various places in the Rhineland called Welling or Wellingen."]},{"name":"Luallen","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Llewellyn  ."]},{"name":"Lewellyn","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Llewellyn  ."]},{"name":"Llewelyn","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Llewellyn  ."]}]},{"name":"Llywelyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(Welsh)  See  Llewelyn ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewelyn","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Llywelyn ap Llywellyn was born in 0999, in Powys, Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Llywelyn de Cymru and Mrs Llywelyn de Cymru. He had at least 1 daughter with Gwenllian ferch John. He died in 1081, in Brecon, Powys, Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 82."},"et":{"0999–1081":"0999–1081","1000–Female":"1000–Surnud","1025–1081":"1025–1081","0965–Male":"0965–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1025":"1025","about 1025":"umbes 1025","1000":"1000","before 0999":"enne 0999","0965":"0965","0999":"0999","1081":"1081","Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Brecon, Powys, Wales":"Brecon, Powys, Wales, United Kingdom","Powys, Wales":"Powys, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"0999–1081":"0999–1081","1000–Female":"1000–Kuollut","1025–1081":"1025–1081","0965–Male":"0965–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1025":"1025","about 1025":"noin 1025","1000":"1000","before 0999":"ennen vuotta 0999","0965":"0965","0999":"0999","1081":"1081","Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Brecon, Powys, Wales":"Brecon, Powys, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Powys, Wales":"Powys, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"0999–1081":"0999–1081","1000–Female":"1000–Décédée","1025–1081":"1025–1081","0965–Male":"0965–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1025":"1025","about 1025":"environ 1025","1000":"1000","before 0999":"avant 0999","0965":"0965","0999":"0999","1081":"1081","Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Galles","Wales":"Galles","Brecon, Powys, Wales":"Brecon, Powys, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Powys, Wales":"Powys, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Llywelyn ap Llywellyn est né en 0999, à Powys, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni, fils de Llywelyn de Cymru et Mrs Llywelyn de Cymru. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Gwenllian ferch John. Il est décédé en 1081, à Brecon, Powys, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni, à l’âge de 82 ans."},"de":{"0999–1081":"0999–1081","1000–Female":"1000–Verstorben","1025–1081":"1025–1081","0965–Male":"0965–Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1025":"1025","about 1025":"um 1025","1000":"1000","before 0999":"vor 0999","0965":"0965","0999":"0999","1081":"1081","Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Monmouth, Monmouthshire, Wales","Wales"